            <div type="translation"> 
                <p>A healer of horses, Nikephoros the pious,
                moved by warm heartfelt desire 
                with like feeling painted the image 
                of the very great martyr George;
                and revently in this monastery of the Phorbia,
                desirous of finding help at [the] Judjement 
                from the most brilliant crowned martyr, 
                and the prayers of those dwelling here.
                (<bibl><ptr target="#Ševčenko2012"/>,<citedRange> 82</citedRange></bibl>)
                </p> 
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The inscription is made up of six lines, which correspond to eight metrical verses. A cross marks the beginning of the poem, while a double dot with a hyphen appears at the end. Τhe single and double points after the words Νικηφόρος, πόθῳ, εἰκόνα, Γεωργίου, Φορβίων, κρίσει, and στεφανίτην denote the end of the verses. Τhe donor of the mural icon, the veterinaria of horses Nikephoros, is probably a different person from the Nikephoros mentioned in the invocation that is inscribed below the metrical poem examined (see <ref target="MedCY.044.105.html">MedCY.044.105</ref>) (<bibl><ptr target="#Ševčenko2012"/>,<citedRange> 83</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#VisCult"/>,<citedRange> 189</citedRange></bibl>). </p>
            </div>
